  <h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Master the Serving Temperature Difference</strong> - Bordeaux reds should be served at 64-68°F to showcase their tannic structure and Cabernet Sauvignon backbone, while Burgundy Pinot Noir performs best at 60-64°F to preserve its delicate aromatics and silky texture. This 4-degree difference is crucial—too warm Burgundy becomes flabby and loses its signature elegance, while too cool Bordeaux will taste harsh and closed.</li>

  <li><strong>Decode the Decanting Decision</strong> - Young Bordeaux (under 10 years) almost always benefits from 1-2 hours of decanting to tame aggressive tannins from Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot, while most Burgundies need only 30-45 minutes maximum—and village-level Burgundies often need no decanting at all. Over-decanting Burgundy can strip away the ethereal aromatics that define great Pinot Noir.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Your Glassware Strategically</strong> - Bordeaux demands a larger bowl (22-26 oz) with a wider opening to aerate the blend and concentrate the darker fruit aromas, while Burgundy shines in a slightly smaller, balloon-shaped glass (16-20 oz) that captures and focuses the wine's more delicate red fruit and earth notes. The Burgundy glass's inward-tapered rim is essential for concentrating those precious aromatics.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Your Peak Drinking Windows</strong> - Quality Bordeaux follows a U-curve: drink within 2-3 years of release or wait 8-15 years for proper development. Burgundy is more forgiving with a gentler aging curve—most Premier Crus hit their stride at 5-8 years and remain excellent for another decade. Grand Cru Burgundy can age 15-20 years but is often approachable much earlier than equivalent-level Bordeaux.</li>

  <li><strong>Read the Vintage Codes</strong> - In Bordeaux, look for years when both Left Bank (Cabernet Sauvignon) and Right Bank (Merlot) succeeded—like 2005, 2009, 2010, and 2016. In Burgundy, prioritize years with dry, warm summers but cool nights like 2005, 2009, 2015, and 2019. Burgundy is more vintage-sensitive due to Pinot Noir's thin skin and susceptibility to rot and dilution.</li>

  <li><strong>Navigate the Classification Systems</strong> - Bordeaux's 1855 Classification and Saint-Émilion's system rank entire châteaux, so you're buying a consistent style. Burgundy's Grand Cru and Premier Cru classifications rank individual vineyard sites, meaning quality varies dramatically by producer within the same vineyard. Always research the producer (négociant vs. domaine) in Burgundy—the who matters more than the where.</li>

  <li><strong>Understand Food Pairing Logic</strong> - Bordeaux's tannin structure and higher alcohol (typically 13-14.5%) make it perfect for rich, protein-heavy dishes like lamb, beef, and aged cheeses that can stand up to the wine's power. Burgundy's higher acidity and lower tannins (typically 12.5-13.5% alcohol) make it ideal for poultry, pork, mushrooms, and dishes with earthy or herbal elements that complement rather than compete.</li>

  <li><strong>Spot Quality Indicators by Region</strong> - In Bordeaux, look for wines with 40+ year old vines (vieilles vignes), hand-harvesting, and at least 12-18 months barrel aging. In Burgundy, seek producers who own their vineyards (domaine-bottled), use indigenous yeasts, and employ minimal filtration. Burgundy's smaller production means even village-level wines from top producers often outperform classified growth Bordeaux at similar price points.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which is more beginner-friendly: Bordeaux or Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Bordeaux is generally more beginner-friendly due to its more accessible price points for quality wines and clearer labeling that often includes grape varieties. Burgundy's complex classification system with its myriad of appellations and climats can be overwhelming for newcomers, plus quality Burgundy typically starts at higher price points. However, both regions offer excellent entry-level options if you know what to look for.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should Bordeaux and Burgundy be served at different temperatures?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, Bordeaux reds should be served slightly warmer at 65-68°F to showcase their bold tannins and complex structure, while Burgundy performs best at 60-63°F to preserve its delicate aromatics and silky texture. Both regions' white wines (Bordeaux Blanc and white Burgundy) should be served chilled at 50-55°F. The temperature difference is crucial because Burgundy's Pinot Noir can become overly alcoholic and lose its elegance if served too warm.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why is Burgundy so much more expensive than Bordeaux?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Burgundy's higher prices stem from dramatically smaller vineyard plots (often just a few acres versus hundreds in Bordeaux) and lower yields due to Pinot Noir's finicky nature. The region produces roughly 10 times less wine than Bordeaux, creating natural scarcity. Additionally, Burgundy's fragmented ownership means many producers make only a few hundred cases of specific appellations, while Bordeaux châteaux can produce thousands of cases of their grand vin.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying Bordeaux vs Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is assuming all Bordeaux wines are bold and all Burgundies are light, when in reality both regions show tremendous diversity. Many people also confuse vintage importance—while Bordeaux vintage variation is significant, Burgundy's producer reputation often matters more than the year. Another major error is buying Burgundy based solely on appellation names without researching the specific producer, as quality varies dramatically even within prestigious villages like Gevrey-Chambertin.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which region offers better value for money: Bordeaux or Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Bordeaux generally offers superior value, especially in the $25-75 range where you can find excellent Cru Bourgeois and Right Bank wines that deliver complexity and ageability. Burgundy's value sweet spot is narrower and typically starts around $40-50 for quality village-level wines from respected producers. However, Bordeaux's classified growth prices have become increasingly inflated, while some Burgundy producers in lesser-known appellations like Monthélie or Santenay offer exceptional value.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Do Bordeaux and Burgundy wines age differently?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, they follow distinctly different aging curves. Quality Bordeaux reds typically need 5-10 years to integrate their tannins and can age gracefully for 20-30+ years, developing leather, tobacco, and earth notes. Burgundy reaches its peak sooner (3-8 years for most wines) and tends to be more fragile with age, though the best examples can last decades while maintaining their signature perfume and silky texture. Burgundy's evolution emphasizes aromatics over structure.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good alternatives if I can't afford top Bordeaux or Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For Bordeaux-style wines, explore Cahors, Madiran, or Washington State Bordeaux blends which offer similar structure at lower prices. For Burgundy alternatives, try Oregon Pinot Noir, particularly from Willamette Valley, or explore Burgundy's satellite regions like Mercurey or Rully which use the same grapes and techniques. German Spätburgunder (Pinot Noir) from Baden or Ahr also provides Burgundian elegance at more accessible prices.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you cellar young Bordeaux and Burgundy in the same conditions?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While both need the same basic storage conditions (55-60°F, 60-70% humidity, darkness), Bordeaux is more forgiving of temperature fluctuations due to its robust tannin structure. Burgundy requires more stable conditions as temperature swings can damage its delicate aromatics and accelerate aging unpredictably. If you must choose, prioritize temperature stability for your Burgundy collection, as a few degrees' variation won't harm most Bordeaux wines as significantly.</p>
